---
import VizPlaceholder from '../VizPlaceholder.astro';

const layers = [
  {
    num: '01',
    name: 'Core platform capabilities',
    body: 'DOM manipulation, AJAX. They just have to exist, not be ergonomic. There is exactly one set of them, because they are tied to the platform itself.',
  },
  {
    num: '02',
    name: 'The framework layer',
    body: 'Defining components, inputs coming in, outputs going out. Surprisingly little variation, and universal: equally good whether you are building a to-do app or a massive banking app.',
  },
  {
    num: '03',
    name: 'The application layer',
    body: 'Routing, server-side rendering, state, data access. It varies too much to normalize. One implementation cannot satisfy everyone, so it takes many.',
  },
];
---

<section id="framework-wars" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      Some history
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      The framework wars
    </h2>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        Twelve years ago the JavaScript world fought a framework war, and the
        lessons took a long time to learn. <mark>The framework that did the
        least won.</mark> React arrived doing far less than its rivals, with no
        router and no data layer, focused on rendering components and turning
        events into more components, and it beat the frameworks that tried to do
        everything. A new layer then grew on top of it and became known as the
        meta-framework. The same fight is starting over AI agents now, and it
        may end the same way.
      </p>
    </div>

    <ol
      class="mt-8 divide-y divide-neutral-800 overflow-hidden rounded-lg border border-neutral-800"
    >
      {
        layers.map((l) => (
          <li class="bg-neutral-950 p-6">
            <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4">
              <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent">{l.num}</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-base font-medium text-neutral-100">{l.name}</h3>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
                  {l.body}
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>

    <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      <p>
        React won on intentional minimalism. It focused on the one layer it
        could make universal, and the one layer where its builders had real
        expertise. That last point matters more than it looks. The people who
        build frameworks are generally not the people who build applications
        with them, and <mark>the same split holds for harnesses today</mark>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Next.js was an implementation, not the implementation. It did not work
        for every React developer, but for a huge segment of the community it
        became the default. It became known as a meta-framework because it sits
        on top of React and completes it, adding the affordances that building
        real applications requires without re-implementing React itself.
      </p>
      <p>
        The layers rhyme with today. LLMs are the new core capability: a few
        things became good enough and an explosion of tooling grew on top.
        Harnesses are the new universal middle layer, so universal that Claude
        Code, Codex, and OpenCode are more similar to each other than the UI
        frameworks of 2013 ever were. And a third layer is now emerging on top
        of them, because every organization is solving the same problems above
        its harnesses. That layer is the <mark>meta-harness</mark>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
    <VizPlaceholder label="two stacked timelines, the 2013 framework layers morphing into the 2026 agent layers" />
  </div>
</section>
